flowchart LR

  subgraph INTENT["1. Path objective"]
    G1["Turn ingress truth into authoritative event-bus truth"]
    G2["Answer where admitted traffic is authoritatively handed off so runtime can begin"]
    G3["Keep bus handoff truth separate from both admission truth and later ingest-commit truth"]
  end

  subgraph ENTRY["2. Entry basis"]
    E1["The entry is admitted ingress event family that has already crossed the boundary and received admit-worthy disposition"]
    E2["It is not raw source data in general"]
    E3["It is not yet receipt truth"]
    E4["Only behavioural_streams are canonical traffic"]
    E5["Arrival, entity, and flow-anchor surfaces are context, not traffic"]
    E6["Traffic stays thin and context is joined inside the platform rather than smuggled into one fat payload"]
    E7["That is why the publish surface is a family of traffic plus context topics, not one topic"]
  end

  subgraph SPINE["5. Broad route logic"]
    R1["Admitted ingress event family"]
    R2["IG publish logic"]
    R3["Pinned traffic and context topics on MSK"]
    R4["Bus-visible handoff to RTDL ingress, context, and join consumers"]
    R5["Authoritative bus truth for downstream runtime"]
  end

  subgraph CARRIES["4. What the path carries"]
    C1["Admitted traffic family: canonical fraud traffic stream itself"]
    C2["Associated arrival and context surfaces that downstream RTDL needs"]
    C3["Pinned topic names"]
    C4["Partition-key rules"]
    C5["Producer and consumer contract"]
    C6["When publication is reconstructable later: topic, partition, and offset truth"]
    C7["The topic map pins the concrete topic family and the partition keys"]
    C8["Traffic and context both partition by merchant_id"]
  end

  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats publish truth as its own truth boundary, not as a casual extension of admission"]
    L2["The system is not saying: once ingress says admit, we can assume runtime got it"]
    L3["It is saying: admit truth and publish truth are different, and the publish boundary must be explicit, authoritative, and reconstructable"]
    L4["That matches the readiness language that admitted events must be published into the event transport network without ambiguity"]
    L5["Truth-ownership boundaries are kept separate across planes"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["The bus is AWS MSK Serverless"]
    S2["The producer boundary is IG"]
    S3["The topic family is pinned by name"]
    S4["Bootstrap and schema-registry handles are pinned"]
    S5["Producer and consumer map is pinned"]
    S6["Fraud traffic topic: ingress -> RTDL ingress"]
    S7["Arrival-events context topic: ingress -> RTDL context"]
    S8["Arrival-entities context topic: ingress -> RTDL context"]
    S9["Flow-anchor context topic: ingress -> RTDL join plane"]
    S10["The publish handoff is concretely seated in named bus, named topics, named partition rules, and named downstream consumers"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The platform wants to preserve thin-traffic semantics while still giving RTDL enough context to work correctly"]
    Y2["That is why the publish boundary is not one giant canonical payload topic"]
    Y3["Traffic stays thin, joins happen inside the platform, and context surfaces are not treated as traffic"]
    Y4["The pinned topic set mirrors that semantic split directly: one traffic topic plus context topics feeding different RTDL consumers"]
    Y5["The current bus shape is driven by system meaning, not incidental implementation convenience"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. What larger contracts are shaping this path"]
    X1["The data-engine contract shapes what may be published as traffic and what must remain context-only"]
    X2["Only behavioural streams are eligible as traffic"]
    X3["Arrival, entity, and flow-anchor surfaces are context for enrichment"]
    X4["Truth products and telemetry are not to be published as business traffic"]
    X5["Topic and contract continuity law shapes where those things are published and who owns them"]
    X6["Existing dev_min topic contracts remain authoritative unless explicitly repinned"]
    X7["Any new topic or schema surface must be pinned in the handles registry first"]
    X8["Ingress and control-plane law shape failure behavior: Kafka topics are authoritative bus surfaces and fail-closed posture is part of platform law"]
    X9["If publish outcome is ambiguous, the system is not allowed to quietly pretend success"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately chooses explicit bus truth over simpler but weaker alternatives"]
    T2["It would be easier to collapse admission and publish into one fuzzy notion of ingress handled it"]
    T3["It would also be easier to publish only one flattened traffic topic and let downstream reconstruct context however it can"]
    T4["The current design rejects that"]
    T5["It pays the cost of maintaining a topic family, explicit producer/consumer contracts, real publish ambiguity handling, and schema/contract continuity"]
    T6["Under aggressive concurrency probe, the live ingress runtime surfaced KAFKA_PUBLISH_TIMEOUT and PUBLISH_AMBIGUOUS, and valid traffic was fail-closed into quarantine rather than silently counted as published"]
    T7["The platform would rather block than lie about bus truth"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["If this path is removed, the platform still has ingress edge, admission boundary, and RTDL components drawn downstream"]
    N2["But it loses the clean truth that connects them"]
    N3["A reviewer could no longer answer where admitted traffic actually enters the runtime network"]
    N4["It would become unclear whether the full event family reached downstream consumers"]
    N5["It would become unclear whether traffic and context separation was preserved"]
    N6["It would become unclear whether publish ambiguity was handled honestly"]
    N7["It would become unclear whether RTDL starvation is publish problem or downstream problem"]
    N8["That weakens A immediately because the system starts looking like a graph with a missing ownership boundary between ingress and runtime"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["The admitted ingress event family has been handed off onto the pinned traffic and context topics"]
    O2["The handoff is authoritative for the downstream RTDL consumers that are supposed to consume it"]
    O3["This path closes earlier than offset/receipt rollup; bus handoff itself is the real truth here"]
    O4["Owned outcome: authoritative bus truth for the admitted traffic and context family"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a distinct job for turning ingress truth into authoritative bus truth"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>the bus handoff is semantically split traffic and context family mirroring the engine's thin-traffic join posture"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>the handoff is concretely seated in MSK Serverless, pinned topic names, pinned partition keys, and pinned IG -> RTDL producer and consumer roles"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>the path is governed by topic continuity, traffic taxonomy, and fail-closed truth-boundary laws"]
    A5["Constraint-awareness claim:<br/>publish ambiguity is treated as a real boundary defect, not silently absorbed as success"]
    A6["A-level meaning:<br/>admitted ingress traffic becomes explicit, semantically correct, contract-governed runtime handoff rather than an implicit continuation"]
  end

